<h3>Question 5</h3>
<div><p><p>What are the objectives that activity planning aims to achieve?</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p>In addition to providing project and resource schedules, activity planning aims to achieve a number of other objectives which may be summarized as follows:</p>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li><strong>Feasibility assessment</strong> Is the project possible within required timescales and resource constraints? It is not until we have constructed a detailed plan that we can forecast a completion date with any reasonable knowledge of its achievability. The fact that a project may have been estimated as requiring two work-years effort might not mean that it would be feasible to complete it within, say, three months were eight people to work on it – that will depend upon the availability of staff and the degree to which activities may be undertaken in parallel.</li>
<li><strong>Resource allocation</strong> What are the most effective ways of allocating resources to the project and when should they be available? The project plan allows us to investigate the relationship between timescales and resource availability (in general, allocating additional resources to a project shortens its duration) and the efficacy of additional spending on resource procurement.</li>
<li><strong>Detailed costing</strong> How much will the project cost and when is that expenditure likely to take place? After producing an activity plan and allocating specific resources, we can obtain more detailed estimates of costs and their timing.</li>
<li><strong>Motivation</strong> Providing targets and being seen to monitor achievement against targets is an effective way of motivating staff, particularly where they have been involved in setting those targets in the first place.</li>
<li><strong>Co-ordination</strong> When do the staff in different departments need to be available to work on a particular project and when do staff need to be transferred between projects? The project plan, particularly with large projects involving more than a single project team, provides an effective vehicle for communication and co-ordination among teams. In situations where staff may need to be transferred between project teams (or work concurrently on more than one project), a set of integrated project schedules should ensure that such staff are available when required and do not suffer periods of enforced idleness.</li>
</ul>
</div>
<h3>Question 6</h3>
<div><p><p>Explain SPM framework.</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p>The Software Project Management (SPM) framework is a structured approach to managing and controlling software development projects effectively. It encompasses various key areas to ensure the project is delivered successfully, meeting its objectives within time, scope, budget, and quality constraints. Here’s an explanation of the key components of the SPM framework:</p>
<ol style="list-style-type:decimal;">
<li><strong>Managing Integration</strong>: Integration involves coordinating various activities and aspects of the project to function cohesively. It includes developing the project charter, defining the scope, and creating a detailed plan to direct and manage the project. Integration also ensures smooth handling of changes through monitoring and control mechanisms.</li>
<li><strong>Managing Scope</strong>: This component ensures that the project&#8217;s goals and boundaries are clearly defined and managed. The project scope is broken down into smaller tasks using a Work Breakdown Structure (WBS). It involves planning, defining, verifying the scope, and controlling scope changes to ensure the project stays aligned with its objectives.</li>
<li><strong>Managing Time/Schedule</strong>: Since projects have a fixed timeline, managing time involves creating and adhering to a project schedule.<br />
This includes defining tasks, estimating durations, sequencing activities, allocating resources, and controlling the schedule to meet deadlines efficiently.</li>
<li><strong>Managing Costs</strong>: Cost management ensures that resources are used efficiently and that project expenses remain within the budget. This involves resource planning, cost estimation, budgeting, and cost control to maximize the value generated by the project while minimizing unnecessary expenditures.</li>
<li><strong>Managing Quality</strong>: Quality management focuses on ensuring that project deliverables meet the desired standards and objectives. It involves planning quality processes, performing quality assurance to maintain standards, and implementing quality control to identify and resolve issues.</li>
<li><strong>Managing Human Resources</strong>: This aspect deals with building and managing a capable project team. It includes planning for human resource needs, hiring suitable personnel, and developing the team to enhance productivity. Managing human resources also ensures that team members perform their roles effectively throughout the project lifecycle.</li>
<li><strong>Managing Communication</strong>: Effective communication is vital for project success as it involves engaging with stakeholders, team members, and other relevant parties. This includes planning communication strategies, distributing information, reporting performance, and managing stakeholder expectations to ensure transparency and alignment.</li>
</ol>
</div>
<h3>Question 7</h3>
<div><p><p>Highlight on different types of contracts.</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p>Contracts are vital in defining the terms and obligations of business engagements. The type of contract selected depends on the nature of the project, the industry, and the degree of risk involved. Here is an overview of the most commonly used types of contracts:</p>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li><strong>Fixed Price (Lump Sum)</strong>: This straightforward contract involves the service provider agreeing to deliver predefined services within a specific period for a fixed payment. It often includes milestones, KPIs, and acceptance criteria, offering the advantage of knowing the total project cost upfront.</li>
<li><strong>Unit Price</strong>: In this model, the project is divided into units with a specific charge for each. This approach provides flexibility, as units can be allocated to various service providers based on expertise and bid amounts. It&#8217;s ideal for projects requiring diverse skill sets across different components.</li>
<li><strong>Cost Plus</strong>: The service provider is reimbursed for all incurred costs (labor, machinery, materials) plus an agreed-upon fee. This contract demands detailed resource schedules and periodic cost reporting, making it transparent but more suitable for projects with uncertain costs.</li>
<li><strong>Incentive</strong>: This contract addresses cost uncertainties, often in innovative or pilot projects. It establishes target price, profit, and maximum cost thresholds. Any cost overruns are shared between the client and provider, balancing risks and promoting efficiency.</li>
<li><strong>Retainer (Time and Material &#8211; T&amp;M)</strong>: This flexible, risk-minimized engagement is based on pricing for time and materials. With short delivery cycles, estimates are sent before each phase, ensuring clarity. It’s often used for long-term relationships, allowing adaptive project evolution.</li>
<li><strong>Percentage of Construction Fee</strong>: Common in engineering projects, this type involves the client paying a percentage of the total construction cost as the service provider&#8217;s fee. It simplifies budgeting while ensuring alignment with the project&#8217;s scale.</li>
</ul>
</div>
